        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Add reply-scoped Telegram stop commands",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nWhat problem does this PR solve?\n\nTelegram `/cancel` and `/stop` currently cannot reliably target the active work tied to a replied-to message, especially when `/stop` is handled as a native Telegram command before the generic reply pipeline sees it.\n\nWhy does this matter now?\n\nOCL-23 needs reply-scoped cancellation in Telegram topics/DMs so a stop command does not cancel unrelated OpenClaw work in the same chat surface.\n\nWhat is the intended outcome?\n\n- Replying `/cancel` or `/stop` to a Telegram request/progress/final bot message resolves the active session that owns that message and aborts only that run.\n- Bare Telegram `/stop` without a reply keeps the existing native current-session behavior.\n- Unknown/completed replied-to messages return a harmless no-active-work response.\n- Message-to-session targeting is stored on the existing session entry, not in a new sidecar file, and Telegram records it through the session-store runtime SDK seam.\n\nWhat is intentionally out of scope?\n\nManual Telegram Web QA is not completed in this PR environment because the available worker does not have a controllable unlocked Telegram Web session.\n\nWhat does success look like?\n\nA Telegram user can reply to a specific active work message with `/cancel` or `/stop`, and OpenClaw stops only that work instead of falling through to broad chat/topic stop behavior.\n\nWhat should reviewers focus on?\n\n- Native Telegram `/stop` ordering in `extensions/telegram/src/bot-native-commands.ts`.\n- Session-entry message target recording/resolution in `src/config/sessions/message-work-targets.ts`.\n- Boundary safety: bundled Telegram uses `openclaw/plugin-sdk/session-store-runtime`, not core deep imports.\n\n## Linked context\n\nWhich issue does this close?\n\nCloses Kaneo OCL-23: Add reply-scoped Telegram /cancel and /stop commands\n\nWhich issues, PRs, or discussions are related?\n\nRelated to the local OCL-23 installed-runtime rework that proved the native `/stop` ordering gap.\n\nWas this requested by a maintainer or owner?\n\nYes, through Kaneo OCL-23.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: reply-scoped Telegram `/cancel` and `/stop` commands for active OpenClaw work.\n- Real environment tested: source branch validation on the local OpenClaw checkout; prior installed-runtime rework was also syntax-checked, gateway-restarted, and Telegram channel-probed against the live local `@an_eye_bot` polling setup.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch: see commands in Tests and validation below.\n- Evidence after fix (screenshot, recording, terminal capture, console output, redacted runtime log, linked artifact, or copied live output): focused tests and typechecks pass locally; prior installed-runtime probe confirmed Telegram polling connected after the native `/stop` hook-order patch.\n- Observed result after fix: tests cover reply-required Telegram stop behavior, `/cancel` aliasing, unknown replied target handling, session message target persistence/resolution, and Telegram native command metadata.\n- What was not tested: live Telegram Web/manual reply flow on this source branch.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: worker-side Telegram Web QA was blocked by the macOS GUI session being locked; the available probe saw `loginwindow`, so browser control/screenshot proof could not be produced from this worker.\n- Before evidence (optional but encouraged): prior OCL-23 rework identified that native Telegram `/stop` could be consumed before generic reply-scoped abort handling.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nWhich commands did you run?\n\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/auto-reply/reply/commands-stop-target.test.ts src/config/sessions.test.ts extensions/telegram/src/bot-native-commands.session-meta.test.ts src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-from-config.test.ts`\n- `pnpm tsgo:core && pnpm tsgo:extensions`\n- `pnpm plugin-sdk:check-exports`\n- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.replies.ts src/auto-reply/reply/commands-session-abort.ts src/auto-reply/reply/commands-stop-target.test.ts src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-from-config.ts src/config/sessions.ts src/config/sessions.test.ts src/config/sessions/message-work-targets.ts src/config/sessions/types.ts src/infra/outbound/deliver.ts src/plugin-sdk/session-store-runtime.ts src/plugins/session-entry-slot-keys.ts`\n- `git diff --check`\n\nWhat regression coverage was added or updated?\n\n- Added `commands-stop-target.test.ts` coverage for Telegram reply-scoped `/stop`, `/cancel`, missing reply, unknown target, and auth rejection.\n- Added session-store coverage for recording and resolving message work targets.\n- Existing Telegram native command metadata coverage was run to protect `ReplyToId` propagation.\n\nWhat failed before this fix, if known?\n\nNative Telegram `/stop` could bypass the generic reply-scoped abort path, and an earlier implementation introduced a JSON sidecar/deep import that violated repo storage and extension-boundary rules.\n\nIf no test was added, why not?\n\nTests were added/updated.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nYes.\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nNo.\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nNo.\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\n\nMapping Telegram message ids to the correct active session without canceling unrelated work.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated?\n\nThe lookup is scoped by channel + chat candidate + replied message id, only applies to Telegram reply-scoped stop/cancel, requires an active abort target for message-scoped cancellation, and falls back to harmless no-active-work text when no target is found.\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action?\n\nReview source changes and run CI/manual Telegram QA if available.\n\nWhat is still waiting on author, maintainer, CI, or external proof?\n\nManual Telegram QA in an unlocked real Telegram DM/topic is still pending.\n\nWhich bot or reviewer comments were addressed?\n\nNo PR comments yet; this PR incorporates the source-level rework after local installed-runtime OCL-23 validation exposed the native `/stop` ordering issue.\n",
